code_changes.content:
{
  "buggy_files": ["sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c"],
  "buggy_functions": ["azx_resume"],
  "confidence": 0.95,
  "reasoning": "The azx_resume function is missing critical IRQ synchronization after acquiring the IRQ during resume from suspend. In comparison to azx_first_init (which properly initializes the driver on probe), azx_resume lacks the synchronize_irq() call that should be made after azx_acquire_irq(). This causes a race condition where the IRQ handler is out of sync with the hardware state after resume. Additionally, the polling_mode and single_cmd flags are not reset during resume, causing the system to remain in degraded modes if they were set before suspend. The missing synchronize_irq() combined with potentially stale polling/single_cmd flags causes codec communication timeouts immediately after resume, triggering the fallback modes (polling -> single_cmd) and resulting in the choppy sound (clicks with silence) reported in the bug. The fix involves: (1) adding synchronize_irq() after azx_acquire_irq() in azx_resume (similar to azx_first_init), and (2) resetting chip->polling_mode and chip->single_cmd to 0 at the beginning of azx_resume to ensure a clean slate after resume."
}

